			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1498">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Reading Edward Abbey [&ldquo;<a href="/article/184">Sincerely, Edward Abbey</a>,&rdquo; October 2006] and Bill McKibben side by side in the same issue of <em>The Sun</em> was a useful study in contrasts. I have just two questions about Abbey: (1) Why did this staunch proponent of negative population growth father two additional children in his final marriage? And (2) did he really drive around in that gas-guzzling old Buick that appears in the accompanying photograph? (Perhaps he was en route to deposit it in the Mariana Trench.)</p>

<p>Abbey&rsquo;s barbs aimed at religion, mysticism, land management, stewardship, <span class="smallcaps">SUV</span>s, and even dogmatic science serve only to undermine the patient dialogue and coalition-building we need to solve our environmental crisis. I don&rsquo;t disagree with the Earth First! approach entirely; sometimes a swift kick in the pants is justified, if only to grab some press coverage. But the likely response by those in power will be to dig their heels in deeper.</p>

<p>McKibben manages to shake the foundations just as much, but does so in a measured, diplomatic, and I dare say optimistic style. This &mdash; and not Abbey&rsquo;s vitriol &mdash; is what will eventually persuade people to beat their swords into plowshares.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Bill Johnson<br>Guilford, Connecticut</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1499">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Edward Abbey writes, to the editor of a student newspaper, &ldquo;What is the essence of the art of writing? Part one: Have something to say. Part two: Say it well.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Great advice, but hard to do most times. Abbey fought the good fight until he died in 1989. Who among us will stand up in his place? What must we do to be heard when the applause has died, when it is all just voices stilled &mdash; or, at least, it appears that way? Poets try their dead level best to illuminate, to be heard, but does anyone have the time now? Self-absorption is so much more entertaining.</p>

<p>Soon we will all join Abbey over the &ldquo;Great Divide.&rdquo; Perhaps it will be clear to us then what he saw. We should look forward to the conversation.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Jim C. Lewis<br>Foster City, California</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1470">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>In the <a href="/issues/373/correspondence">January 2007 Correspondence</a> Bill Johnson points out that Edward Abbey drove a gas-guzzling Buick (he didn&rsquo;t mention the Ford pickups) and spawned too many children (so did Al Gore). Abbey&rsquo;s faults were more glaring and public than most, and anyone who has read his work already knows them well. But Johnson is wrong to say that Abbey was counterproductive. Just ask the thousands of readers he has influenced, even years after his death.</p>

<p>Abbey told ugly truths when nobody else would, and like nobody else can. Of course we need the Bill McKibbens of the world to speak out calmly and rationally and attempt to sway those who are inclined to listen and intelligent enough to understand. But when an ignorant, sleazy asshole builds another senseless &ldquo;development,&rdquo; we need people like Abbey to call him an ignorant, sleazy asshole. Abbey&rsquo;s vitriol was often (not always) appropriate and necessary, and it sprang from his deep love for our little planet.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Wayne Steffens<br>Two Harbors, Minnesota</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

				<div class="text-center">
			<button class="b b-1 xsmall js-b-readmore-correspondence" data-collapsible="#article-correspondences" data-label="Read More Letters">Read More Letters</button>
		</div>
			</div>
    
